Mixin: Music Annotation Exploratory Analysis¶

Overview of the Mixin Project¶

The Quest for an AI DJ¶

The year is 2024. Rapid developments in technology have revived a question that scholars have contemplated for eons: Can I teach my computer how to DJ?

The Mixin project aims to develop an autonomous DJ system that can select songs from an input playlist and arrange them into seamless, continuous mix—a feat traditionally reserved for carbon-based disc jockeys.

Project Stages and Objectives¶

1) Automated Chorus Identification: Accurately identify the parts of a song to play, skip, or use for transitions.

2) Algorithmic Song Selection: Design an algorithm to assemble the optimal sequence of tracks that creates a smooth, natural flow based on features like keys, tempos, and energies.

3) Transition Engineering: Leverage audio signal processing and music theory to design transitions that are audibly indistinguishable from those performed by a skilled human DJ.

Current Stage: Automated Chorus Identification¶

The essence of DJing revolves around the art of storytelling through music. This narrative is sculpted not just by the selection of music, but by the mastery over which segments of these tracks are played or mixed. In this context, the ability to discern which musical segments to play, skip, or use for transitions is an essential skill for all DJs. Similarly, the ability to set, save, and recall cue points is an industry standard feature for DJ softwares. This process resembles the traditional vinyl DJ practice of setting cue points - physical stickers placed on records to mark significant moments. This practice requires a deep familiarity with each track and strategic foresight into how each segment could be woven into the broader narrative of the set. For an AI DJ system like Mixin, the challenge is to embed this nuanced understanding of musical structure and emotional progression into algorithms capable of analyzing audio features. The current stage aims to automate the process of setting cue points, specifically cue points that demarcate the beginning and end of a core thematic segment (i.e. chorus) of a song.

Exploratory Analysis¶

The exploratory data analysis in this stage will consist of:

  • Data Profiling: To gain a comprehensive understanding of the dataset, including the types of data, volume, hierarchical strucutre, and general characteristics
  • Label Validation: To assess the quality of manually labeled chorus segments, beat-grid generation, and tempo estimation in the absence of ground truth data.
  • Audio Feature Generation & Visualization: To extract features from an audio signal and visualize them to understand the characteristics of various audio features relevant to DJing.
  • Insights and Findings: To summarize and discuss the findings of the exploratory data analysis.

Data Profile¶

Data Collection¶

Data for this project were personally labeled by a carbon-based disc jockey. Refer to the "Mixin Data Annotation Guide" for a comprehensive understanding of the criteria and methodology used for labeling chorus segments. The guide is accessible here.

def get_summary(df):
    """Generates a summary dataframe with descriptive statistics and example values."""
    # Add example value for all columns (numeric and non-numeric)
    example_value = df.apply(lambda x: np.random.choice(x.dropna().values) 
                             if not x.dropna().empty else np.nan)
    
    # Construct the initial summary dataframe with general info
    summary_df = pd.DataFrame({
        'Non-NA Count': df.notna().sum(),
        'NA Count': df.isna().sum(),
        'Unique Values': df.nunique(dropna=False),
        'Data Type': df.dtypes,
        'Example Value': example_value
    })
    
    # Compute descriptive statistics for numeric columns and merge with summary_df
    summary_df = summary_df.join(df.describe().T.rename(columns={
        'mean': 'Mean', 'std': 'Std', 'min': 'Min',
        '25%': '25th Percentile', '50%': 'Median',
        '75%': '75th Percentile', 'max': 'Max'
    }), how='left')
    
    return summary_df

get_summary(df)

Genre Association Network¶

In [221]:
import networkx as nx
import math
import plotly.graph_objs as go

# Initialize graph and get top genres
G = nx.Graph()
top_genres = list(sorted_genre_artist_counts.keys())[:50]  # Ensure this is predefined

# Build genre-artist associations
genre_artist_counts = {}
for genres, artists in df_genres[df_genres['sp_genre'].apply(lambda x: any(g in x for g in top_genres))][['sp_genre', 'Artists']].values:
    artists_set = set(artists.split('/'))
    for genre in genres:
        if genre in top_genres:
            genre_artist_counts.setdefault(genre, set()).update(artists_set)

# Add nodes based on genre artist counts
for genre, artists in genre_artist_counts.items():
    G.add_node(genre, size=len(artists))

# Add edges between genres sharing artists
for genres in df_genres['sp_genre']:
    for genre1 in genres:
        for genre2 in genres:
            if genre1 in top_genres and genre2 in top_genres and genre1 != genre2:
                weight = 1 + G[genre1][genre2]['weight'] if G.has_edge(genre1, genre2) else 1
                G.add_edge(genre1, genre2, weight=weight)

# Layout calculation and edge/node extraction
pos = nx.spring_layout(G, k=0.3, iterations=50)
edge_x, edge_y = [], []
for edge in G.edges():
    x0, y0, x1, y1 = *pos[edge[0]], *pos[edge[1]]
    edge_x.extend([x0, x1, None])
    edge_y.extend([y0, y1, None])

node_x, node_y = zip(*[pos[node] for node in G.nodes()])
node_sizes = [10 * math.sqrt(G.nodes[node]['size']) for node in G.nodes()]

# Plot configuration
edge_trace = go.Scatter(x=edge_x, y=edge_y, line=dict(width=0.5, color='#888'), mode='lines', hoverinfo='none')
node_trace = go.Scatter(x=node_x, y=node_y, mode='markers', hoverinfo='text', marker=dict(
    showscale=True, colorscale='YlGnBu', size=node_sizes, color=node_sizes, line_width=2,
    colorbar=dict(thickness=15, title='Node Connections', xanchor='left', titleside='right')))

node_trace.text = [f'{node}: {G.nodes[node]["size"]} artists' for node in G.nodes()]

fig = go.Figure(data=[edge_trace, node_trace], layout=go.Layout(
    title='Genre Association Network', showlegend=False, hovermode='closest',
    margin=dict(b=20, l=5, r=5, t=40), xaxis=dict(showgrid=False, zeroline=False, showticklabels=False),
    yaxis=dict(showgrid=False, zeroline=False, showticklabels=False), width=800, height=600))

fig.show()

Label Validation¶

In this section, we aim to evaluate the quality of our manually labeled chorus segments, beat-grid generation algorithm, and tempo estimation methods. Beat-grids allow us to quantize songs into beats and bars, which are meaningful units in the structure of music. Quantizing, in this context, means partitioning our data into these units to enable a deep learning model to predict patterns over time effectively.

Underlying Assumption¶

It's important to note that this evaluation is conducted in the absence of an external ground truth for direct comparison. Instead, we are banking on the hypothesis that a strong alignment between the chorus labels and an independently generated beat-grid and tempo estimation signifies proximity to what would be considered the "true" structure of the song. This alignment-based approach to validation assumes that both the manual labeling process and the algorithmic estimations accurately capture the essential features of the music, thereby enabling the autonomous DJ system to perform seamlessly. To this end, we will also A/B test different estimation parameters to see which one yields the best alignment with chorus labels.

Methodology¶

The methodology adopted for this evaluation includes:

  1. Manual Labeling: During the labeling process, choruses were marked such that the start of a chorus segment aligns with the first down-beat of the first bar, while the end of the chorus segment is marked after the last down-beat of the last bar plays to completion. This process was aided by DJ software, which provided a visual representation of the song's spectrogram over a beat grid.
  2. Beat-Grid Algorithm Development: Since the spectrogram and beat grid provided by Serato DJ are proprietary features, I developed a custom beat grid generating algorithm using dynamic programming. These algorithms are key to autonomously identifying and aligning song choruses without manual intervention.
  3. Alignment Evaluation: We will evaluate how well the manually labeled chorus segments align with the beat grid and tempo generated by our algorithms. This alignment serves as a proxy measure for the accuracy of our manual labeling and the efficacy of the beat-grid and tempo estimation algorithms.
  4. A/B Testing parameters against spotify-generated features: We will generate beat-grids with our own tempo estimation methods, librosa's tempo estimation method, and Spotify's tempo estimation method, and see which one aligns better with the manually labeled choruses.

Assessment Metrics¶

Alignment Accuracy¶

Alignment Accuracy measures how well the start and end times of manually labeled choruses align with the beats identified by the beat-grid algorithm. It can be quantified using the Root Mean Square Error (RMSE) between the labeled chorus timestamps and the nearest beat grid timestamps.

  • Root Mean Square Error (RMSE):
    $$RMSE = \sqrt{\frac{1}{N} \sum_{i=1}^{N} (t_{i} - \hat{t}_{i})^2}$$ where $N$ is the total number of chorus start or end points, $t_{i}$ is the timestamp of the $i$-th labeled chorus point, and $\hat{t}_{i}$ is the timestamp of the nearest beat grid point to $t_{i}$.

Tempo Consistency¶

Tempo Consistency can be evaluated by comparing the BPM (beats per minute) estimated by the algorithm to the tempo implied by the distribution of choruses over the beat grid. A simple way to mathematically assess this is by calculating the Pearson correlation coefficient between the tempo variations within each chorus and the overall estimated tempo.

  • Pearson Correlation Coefficient:
    $$r = \frac{\sum (x_i - \bar{x})(y_i - \bar{y})}{\sqrt{\sum (x_i - \bar{x})^2 \sum (y_i - \bar{y})^2}}$$
    where $x_i$ represents the tempo variations within choruses, and $y_i$ represents the estimated tempo for those segments. A higher correlation indicates better tempo consistency.

Rhythmic Accuracy¶

Rhythmic Accuracy focuses on how uniformly the chorus segments are distributed in relation to the beat grid, indicating the precision of rhythmic elements captured by the labels and algorithms. This can be assessed using the Normalized Cross-Correlation (NCC) between the onset of chorus segments and the beat grid.

  • Normalized Cross-Correlation (NCC):
    $$NCC(\tau) = \frac{1}{N(\tau)} \sum_{n} \frac{(x[n] - \mu_x)(y[n - \tau] - \mu_y)}{\sigma_x \sigma_y}$$
    where $x[n]$ represents the signal indicating the onset of chorus segments, $y[n]$ is the beat grid signal, $\tau$ is the lag, $N(\tau)$ is the normalization factor (number of overlaps at lag $\tau$), and $\mu_x, \mu_y, \sigma_x, \sigma_y$ are the means and standard deviations of $x$ and $y$ signals, respectively. The maximum value of NCC over all $\tau$ can be taken as a measure of rhythmic alignment; a higher NCC indicates better rhythmic accuracy.
